## Proposed Changes

---

### Phase 1: Clean Architecture Separation (3-Way Switch)

We will extract the charting logic from `App.jsx` into a unified `ChartController`. This controller will mount either Canvas 2D, WebGL, or WebGPU based on a 3-way toggle switch.

#### [NEW] `src_demo/components/ChartController.jsx`
- Acts as the parent container.
- Holds the shared state for the viewport (visible time range and price range).
- Renders `<Canvas2DEngine />`, `<WebGLChartEngine />`, or `<WebGPUChartEngine />`.

#### [NEW] `src_demo/components/Canvas2DEngine.jsx`
- A clean, isolated component containing ONLY the Lightweight Charts logic.

#### [NEW] `src_demo/components/WebGPUChartEngine.jsx`
- A dedicated engine utilizing modern WebGPU for ultra-high-performance rendering.
- Custom WGSL (WebGPU Shading Language) pipelines for complex visual effects if needed.

---

### Phase 2: Native WebGL & WebGPU Drawings

We will add dedicated interactive layers for both GPU engines to draw and manipulate tools natively on the GPU.

#### [MODIFY] `src_demo/components/WebGLChartEngine.jsx` & [NEW] `src_demo/components/WebGPUChartEngine.jsx`
- Implement native interaction events (`pointerdown`, `pointermove`, `pointerup`) to allow the user to draw directly on the GPU canvas.
- Create native rendering pipelines for:
  - Lines (Trendlines, Rays, Horizontal Lines)
  - Text (Labels)
  - Polygons (Fibonacci Retracements)
  - Indicators (SMA, EMA, RSI)
- For WebGPU, drawing pipelines will be strictly optimized for `preference: 'webgpu'` using Pixi v8.

---

### Phase 3: Universal State Synchronization (The "Bridge")

When the user clicks the 3-way toggle (Canvas 2D -> WebGL -> WebGPU), we must ensure zero data loss.

#### [MODIFY] `src_demo/store/drawingStore.js`
- Ensure the store holds purely mathematical data (e.g., `{ id, type, points: [{time, price}], color }`).
- Both engines will strictly read and write to this unified format.
- When toggling, the `ChartController` will fetch the exact `visibleLogicalRange` from the active engine and pass it as the `initialViewport` to the incoming engine.

